<TITLE> Cold snap and Easter boost John Lewis store sales </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 London, April 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British retailer John Lewis Partnership reported a 1.3 percent rise in weekly department store sales on Friday as a cold and wet Easter week drove people indoors to go shopping. The employee-owned group said total group sales fell 2.2 percent from the year-earlier period, however, dragged down by a 4.6 percent drop in takings at its upmarket Waitrose supermarkets. "To really make sense of our performance we will have to wait until the end of April to take a balanced view without the distortions caused by the earlier fall of Easter," said Barry Matheson, John Lewis's head of Selling Development. "One of the coldest, wettest Easter Mondays that I can remember got us off to a flying start," said Matheson, adding that strong gadget sales contrasted with sales of outdoor goods. "If we measure ourselves against the same Easter week last year ... we achieved a stunning 15 percent rise." John Lewis's weekly sales figures are closely watched as an indicator of broader trends on Britain's high streets and shopping centres, although the group caters primarily for more affluent shoppers. Retail analysts have been painting a bleak picture as indebted Britons rein in discretionary spending to manage higher mortgage interest rates and rising food and energy bills. Sales at John Lewis's most exclusive outlet, Peter Jones, on London's Sloane Square, have been hit hardest this year, an indication that shoppers are slashing their spending on luxury items. The Peter Jones store's latest week's sales took another nose dive, coming in 21 percent lower than a year ago. For the group as whole for the nine weeks to March 29, sales were up 5.8 perce
